Pour the @water for the bulgur{220%ml} into a large #saucepan{}, stir in half the
@chicken stock paste{20%g} and bring to the boil. Stir in the @bulgur wheat{120%g},
bring back up to the boil and simmer for ~{1%minute}.

Pop a lid on the pan and remove from the heat. Leave to the side for
~{12-15%minutes} or until ready to serve.

Meanwhile, heat a large #frying pan{} on medium-high heat (no oil). Once hot,
add the @British beef mince{240%g} and fry until browned, ~{5-6%minutes}.
Use a #spoon{} to break it up as it cooks.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw mince.

While the mince cooks, cut the @dried apricots{40%g} into small pieces.

When the mince has browned, drain and discard any excess fat. Season with
@salt{} and @ground black pepper{}. Stir in the @chermoula spice mix{1%sachet},
apricots, @tomato puree{30%g}, @red pepper chilli jelly{25%g},
@water for the sauce{175%ml} and remaining chicken stock paste.

> IMPORTANT: The mince is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Bring the chermoula beef to the boil, then reduce the heat and simmer gently
until thickened, ~{4-6%minutes}.

Once the sauce has thickened, add the @baby spinach{40%g} to the pan a handful
at a time until wilted and piping hot, ~{1-2%minutes}. Remove from the heat
and season with salt and pepper. Add a splash of water if a little too thick.

Share the bulgur wheat between your #serving bowls{} and spoon over the
chermoula beef.

Finish with a dollop of @Greek style natural yoghurt{75%g} on top.

Enjoy!